<div id="comment-dVqZXbtXS06ma69nAXHc9Q-content" class="content">
<p><b>&#64;koziol.mutant</b> If I were France, I would let Morocco have the ball, drop back deep and counterattack with Mbappe and Dembele&#58; whoever drives the ball down on the wing, the other should run with him and suddenly cut back into the middle inside the box to finish the situation with a goal. Mbappe and Dembele are similar speedy players, and there&#39;s no way that the Moroco defenders could keep up with them. Also, with this counterattack strategy, Bono has minimal chance to showcase his goalkeeping prowess as the winger cutting inwards inside the box will not only cut ahead of any defender who might be there, but also cut ahead of the goalkeeper as well. In case Morocco doesn&#39;t fall for this con &#40;namely, stays on his own playing field possessing the ball&#41;, then we are in for extra time and then penalty kicks. Unless, Tchouameni surprises us with a similar unexpected, key first goal as he did against England. The other option would be set pieces, because the 1st goal will be key in such a game</p>

<div id="comment-so8IYCduHEC5S69nAU-ubA-content" class="content">
<p><b>&#64;3shots</b> I remember one match, I think it was when either Bulgaria or Romania was denied a win. Sepp Blatter was in the stadium. Around that time there was a lot of debate about allowing VAR into the game. As Blatter was sitting there, the goal was broadcast on a giant screen in the stadium, including a camera show above goal showing the ball going over the line, clearly. Everyone in the stadium, other than the ref and Blatter, could see that. THAT IS the technology that&#39;s needed. A linesman could watch a set of camera angles instead of chasing the ball along the line and squinting his eyes and immediately raise his flag, but no. Instead we have to stop the game and waste time wondering whether the officials are as blind as Blatter. Blatter, incidentally, was dead against VAR because he claimed that 10 men could have 10 different opinions about whether a ball was or was not over the line. I thought logic dictated that it could only be two opinions, but no, he was correct. Only in footer</p>
</div>

<div id="comment-ilH9I3v3pECC6q9hAYeF-A-content" class="content">
<p>this is very exciting, both teams have the ambition to attack &#38; have star quality &#38; a lot of firepower going forward, but dont get it twisted, frances greatest strength is still counterattacks, not some crazy creativity in midfield. having both mbappe &#38; dembele is pretty devastating but poland honestly dealt with the counterattacks pretty well &#40;even when they didnt park the bus &#38; leave 5 players back - more like 3 which is still something&#41; tho were still outclassed by mbappe &#38; girouds individual quality. as such i honestly expect england to be the slightly more dominant side here. the kinda spaces and chances both teams allowed their opponents in the previous round were similar. i think englands a bit more well-rounded &#38; rigorous but for some reason their past &#43; frances devastating incisiveness when they get the chance makes the french more likely to win a one-off match. if early goal, itll turn into a 2-3 goalfest &#38; open game as expected. if no early goal, 1-0 tactical closed battle</p>
</div>
